{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01DszTVYx8PrdTNbdc425ftL","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Based on my investigation, I can now provide the diagnosis.\n\nThe `git diff` shows exactly one line changed in the buggy commit — in `libyara/parser.c` at the rule-declaration duplicate-identifier check. External variables are added to `compiler->objects_table` with `NULL` as their namespace (compiler.c:915), but the buggy code now looks them up using `compiler->current_namespace->name`. That mismatch means a rule whose identifier matches an external variable's identifier passes the duplicate check undetected, corrupting the compiled rules object. When `test_scanner` then calls `yr_scanner_scan_mem` on the malformed scanner (scanner's rules or state is invalid), the execution path through `yr_scanner_scan_mem_blocks` returns `ERROR_SUCCESS (0)` instead of reaching the `ERROR_CALLBACK_REQUIRED` guard at scanner.c:344.\n\n---\n\n**ROOT CAUSE:** `libyara/parser.c:733` — the hash-table lookup that checks whether a rule name collides with an external variable uses `compiler->current_namespace->name` instead of `NULL` as the namespace key. External variables are stored in `objects_table` under the `NULL` namespace (compiler.c:915), so the lookup never finds them. A rule whose name matches an external variable identifier is silently allowed, producing a malformed compiled-rules object. The downstream effect is that `yr_scanner_scan_mem` returns `0` (ERROR_SUCCESS) instead of `ERROR_CALLBACK_REQUIRED (14)` when called without a callback.\n\n**LOCAL FIX:** Revert line 733 in `libyara/parser.c` from `compiler->current_namespace->name` back to `NULL`:\n```c\n// before (buggy)\nyr_hash_table_lookup(\n    compiler->objects_table,\n    identifier,\n    compiler->current_namespace->name) != NULL)\n\n// after (fixed)\nyr_hash_table_lookup(\n    compiler->objects_table,\n    identifier,\n    NULL) != NULL)\n```\nThis makes the duplicate check consistent with how external variables are stored — namespace-agnostic.\n\n**GLOBAL FIX:** Introduce a helper `yr_compiler_lookup_object(compiler, identifier)` that encapsulates the namespace-independent lookup of external variables, and use it everywhere objects_table is queried for existence checks. This eliminates the repeated, error-prone inline assumption that external variables live in the `NULL` namespace, and makes any future namespace refactoring a single-point change rather than scattered `NULL` literals spread across compiler.c and parser.c."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":413,"cache_read_input_tokens":42230,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":413},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9f56b958-0e33-435a-9ab4-3d32cef4928f","uuid":"f0c3b64a-055b-4c04-9277-109d5ce6da01"}
